"n.奸商，牟取暴利者 【英】 n. 奸商，牟取暴利者(on e who makes an unreasonable profit) 【记】 profit(利润)+eer(人 )→赚利润之人→奸商 【例】 The profiteer sold items in short supply for very high prices. n. 奸商(供应短缺时牟取暴利者) 【记】源于: profit(n 利润) 【记】profit + eer 人，赢利之人，比常见的er 多个e 指的是奸商 profiteer (v.)  1797, but dormant in English until it was revived in World War I, from profit + -eer. From 1912 as a noun. Related: Profiteering (1814). Or is it simply hysteria which produces what is to-day termed ""the profiteer?"" It is probable that the modern profiteer is the same person whom we formerly called ""the grafter, the extortioner, the robber, the gouger."" [""Legal Aid Review,"" April 1920]"
